snippet.textDisplay: My unit was originally supposed to go to Ramadi during this time, but our deployment got delayed by three months so we ended up on the south side of Baghdad instead. I had the honor and pleasure to serve beside and train with all the branches of the military (including most Special Forces units) while down range, and I appreciated this former Navy Seal pointing this out. Literally the only branch I never worked beside was the Coast Guard, but that's because they don't deploy overseas. Also the absolute worst (or most unrealistic) military movie I've ever seen was Hurt Locker. I could care less that it won a bunch of awards. Anyone who's actually served in the military would despise that movie.

snippet.textDisplay: A lot of people trash the military because sometimes we killed innocent people. Heres the issue. When you're fighting Islamic Radical groups, they have no real uniform. So in a city like that, anyone can be a threat. Militants wore regular civilian clothing. So lets say you start taking fire. All that militant has to do, is run away, run behind a block, drop his gun and he'd pretend he was a regular civilian. It wasn't like WW2 where you KNEW that guy was a German or Japanese. Even in Korea/Vietnam, it was usually obvious if the person was a combatant. So often times, Militants would use schools, hospitals, etc as a "human shield". So when we opened fire in return, you might have taken out the target, but 3 civilians died next to the Militant. Its a shame, but thats why fighting Terrorists is difficult. We never "meant" to hurt them, but Terrorists will take civilians on purpose in order to use them as shields. They realize that our media would whine. Its a good tactic, but of course an evil tactic.
